																			<td valign="top"
																				style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #333333; font-size: 12px; text-align: justify;">
																				All news channels and newspaper headlines are
																				screaming that India is not shining anymore. The
																				rupee is falling, government paralysis on every
																				policy decision, untamable inflation, corruption in
																				every walk of life and more. And worst of all
																				against a projected 9%, our growth rate today is
																				only 6.1% - a 30% drop. Can it get any worse? <br />
																				<br /> Let's slightly look into our past. In the
																				last 50 years, our average growth rate has been
																				5.0%. In the 1960s growth rate was 6.7%, 1970s -
																				2.9%, 1980s - 5.7%, 1990s - 5.6%, 2000s - 7.2%. So
																				far in this decade, it is 8.0%. Are we not doing
																				much better now than in the past? In the last ten
																				years equity markets have returned 16.89% CAGR, far
																				far better than most economies around the world, but
																				we seem to think we are doing bad. <br /> <br />
																				The objective here is not to brush aside the
																				concerns. There are some problems and they are real.
																				Just that they are not really as bad as they seem,
																				or as they are made out to be. The problem is our
																				reference point. <br /> <br /> Leaving the macro
																				economy to the learned few, what does it mean to
																				investors in general and you and I in
																				particular?&nbsp; Most investors, at least the ones
																				who jumped into the equity markets in the last 3
																				years talk about opportunity cost or opportunity
																				lost by staying invested in the equities. &nbsp; <br />
																				<br /> &quot;All this theory, that in the long run
																				markets will perform better than other asset classes
																				and stuff is okay, but what about the losses I have
																				already made?&quot; argue many investors. In the
																				last two years, equity markets have moved down over
																				20%. From here on, the portfolio will have to make
																				up the losses of the previous years and then return
																				YOY over 20% if not more, depending on how far your
																				goal is, to get there! <br /> <br /> This logic
																				and arithmetic is perfect. The assumption is not. <br />
																				<br /> Remember the disclaimer ‘past performance
																				are not an indicator of the future’ and this is
																				applicable both when markets have been good and bad
																				in the past, at least the near past.&nbsp; In the
																				long run, history does repeat itself. And there is
																				enough proof to this, at least from the stock
																				markets. <br /> <br /> Markets rebound, quite
																				smartly at that after a good correction. They did
																				between 2008 and 2009 – over 100%. But since then
																				they are just stuck there. It would be interesting
																				to note that corrections are of two types – price
																				corrections and time corrections. What we are seeing
																				now are time corrections. Between 2008 and 2009 too
																				much happened too fast. That should have ideally
																				happened in 4-5 years. And so, the market is biding
																				time. We continue to be range bound in the last 3
																				years and are at the same levels we were in 2009. <br />
																				<br /> Historically, investments made when P/E is
																				less than 16, have in the next 4-5 years returned
																				over 20% CAGR. But that is when most investors have
																				lost faith and exited markets also. Markets today
																				hover at about 14-15 P/E. <br /> <br /> <strong>But
																					what if the goal is nearing and your assumptions go
																					very wrong? </strong><br /> Assumptions can go wrong, they
																				will. Let’s draw a comparison with missile warheads.
																				The most sophisticated and most useful ones are the
																				guided missiles. Guided missiles have some sort of
																				guidance mechanism like infra red or laser
																				radiations systems to identify target. When the
																				missile takes off the target is located to be at a
																				specific place. Wind direction, obstructions on the
																				path and certain other parameters are assumed and
																				based on that the flight system is programmed. <br />
																				<br /> <strong>Assume that the target
																					moves or some new obstruction come onto the path.
																					Will the missile be abandoned? </strong><br /> The missile
																				changes course to attack the target. When there is
																				heavier wind or obstructions on the path the
																				guidance system maneuvers the missile in flight, on
																				the go and counters inaccuracies.&nbsp; And the
																				missile will attempt hitting the target within a
																				certain radius, in such a way that the target even
																				if not exactly hit will feel the impact well enough.
																				<br /> <br /> A financial plan attempts to do
																				exactly that. The goal is projected and returns are
																				assumed. The goal can move with time and so can
																				assumptions go terribly wrong. The plan cannot be
																				abandoned. But course corrections are to be done. <br />
																				<br /> If the course correction means change asset
																				allocation, make a one-time investment, increase
																				regular investments, liquidate some assets, borrow
																				to pitch in or whatever makes logical and economic
																				sense, so be it. <br /> <br /> Financial planning
																				is a process designed with the objective of reaching
